Note that the fibres of the mylohyoid run perpendicular to those of the anterior belly of the digastric muscle. Each mylohyoid arises from the medial surface of the body of the mandible. Its posterior fibers attach to the hyoid bone and its more anterior fibers blend with those of the mylohyoid on the opposite side in a midline band of connective tissue called a raphe. The mylohyoid muscles form the floor of the mouth, and they are innervated by the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (V3).
